 Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Overleden","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Deceased","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Colaton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: from a Middle English personal name, <i>Colstan</i>, which is probably from Old Norse <i>Kolsteinn</i>, composed of the elements <i>kol</i> ‘charcoal’ + <i>steinn</i> ‘stone’. This name has probably been confused with   Coulson  .","English: habitational name from Colston Basset in Nottinghamshire, or the nearby Carcolston, both of which seem to have originally been named from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kolr</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. The first syllable of Car Colson was originally the defining prefix <i>kirk</i> ‘church’.","English: habitational name from Coulston in Wiltshire, which is named with the genitive case of an Old English personal name <i>Cufel</i> (diminutive of <i>Cufa</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Coulson","meanings":["English (North Midlands and northern England): variant of   Colson  .","Irish (Fermanagh): from a shortened form of   McCool  , with the addition of the English patronymic suffix <i>-son</i> in place of the Gaelic prefix <i>mac</i>."]},{"name":"Coulston","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Colston  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Colaton was born in 1330, in Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Surnud","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Kuollut","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Décédé","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Roger Colaton est né en 1330, à Colyton, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Verstorben","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1368":"1368","1388":"1388","1330":"1330","Collaton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Roger Colaton wurde 1330 in Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1330–Deceased":"1330–Desede","